The paper discusses the design and performance of associative memories, which are commonly studied in the fields of neural networks and machine learning. The consideration of noisy internal computations suggests a focus on neural networks, which is reflected in the likely sub-categories of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The use of graph-based inference algorithms and the potential application to biological neuronal networks suggest a possible connection to cs.SY (Systems and Control) and cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). Finally, the overall topic of associative memory design and performance could also fall under the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence).
